498
00:21:57,480 --> 00:21:59,140
fun energy about them.

499
00:21:59,140 --> 00:22:01,680
And that is not a substitute for preparation.

500
00:22:01,680 --> 00:22:05,420
So they both seemed lovely and happy and fun and nice.

501
00:22:05,420 --> 00:22:08,060
And also, it was a mess.

502
00:22:08,060 --> 00:22:09,640
And a lot of people's names were messed up.

503
00:22:09,640 --> 00:22:17,600
And there was the one author who was not mentioned entirely as a finalist until the entire audience began to shout.

504
00:22:17,600 --> 00:22:18,580
Who was that?

505
00:22:18,580 --> 00:22:19,600
Camilla Cole.

506
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:20,900
I did not know that.

507
00:22:20,900 --> 00:22:22,320
Which I hope I'm saying correctly.

508
00:22:22,320 --> 00:22:23,380
Oh, yeah.

509
00:22:23,380 --> 00:22:24,340
Is that Astounding Award?

510
00:22:24,340 --> 00:22:25,500
I think it was Astounding Award.

511
00:22:25,500 --> 00:22:27,120
It's Lodestown, I think.

512
00:22:27,500 --> 00:22:28,060
Oh, I'm sorry.

513
00:22:28,060 --> 00:22:28,520
Thank you.

514
00:22:28,520 --> 00:22:29,500
Lodestown Award.

515
00:22:29,500 --> 00:22:31,940
It was, she was the last one on the list.

516
00:22:31,940 --> 00:22:36,840
And apparently her name was printed on a second sheet, according to what Kay Tempest Bradford said.

517
00:22:36,840 --> 00:22:39,600
She said, oh, there's a, she read the first five.

518
00:22:39,600 --> 00:22:41,200
And she said, and the winner is.

519
00:22:41,200 --> 00:22:46,400
And then the whole audience began yelling and shouting and saying, you left one off.

520
00:22:46,400 --> 00:22:48,760
And she said, oh, no, did I leave one off?

521
00:22:48,760 --> 00:22:50,820
And then she said, oh, there it is.

522
00:22:50,820 --> 00:22:52,120
It's on a second sheet of paper.

523
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:57,980
And then I understand in the moment you're embarrassed and you're casting about for something to say.

524
00:22:58,060 --> 00:23:00,980
And she said, well, she's on a separate sheet of paper.

525
00:23:00,980 --> 00:23:02,200
She must be the winner.

526
00:23:02,200 --> 00:23:05,540
Oh, and then she wasn't the winner.

527
00:23:05,540 --> 00:23:06,440
Oh, no.

528
00:23:06,440 --> 00:23:07,580
It was a lot.

529
00:23:07,580 --> 00:23:08,920
It was really uncomfortable.

530
00:23:09,040 --> 00:23:12,920
And I mean, I was just sitting there minding my business and I was uncomfortable.

531
00:23:12,920 --> 00:23:16,100
So I can't imagine how that finalist felt.

532
00:23:16,100 --> 00:23:18,880
Probably really bad and awkward and.

533
00:23:18,880 --> 00:23:22,200
Every muscle in my body clenched at thinking about that.

534
00:23:22,200 --> 00:23:25,580
I'm not sure I can bring myself to watch it.

535
00:23:25,580 --> 00:23:26,260
Yeah.

536
00:23:26,260 --> 00:23:27,440
Oh, no.

537
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:30,640
We could just stop recording if everyone needs to just lie down.

538
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:35,140
This is in some ways a dead art now, but I'm quite good at print layout.

539
00:23:35,420 --> 00:23:40,440
Some listeners will know that I was deputy division head for publications for LUNCON in 2014.

540
00:23:40,440 --> 00:23:43,160
But I also often do like Eastcon newsletters.

541
00:23:43,160 --> 00:23:50,660
Like the very first volunteering job I ever did at a convention was when I did the program for my second convention, which was Year of the Teladu.

542
00:23:50,660 --> 00:23:52,380
So I have opinions about layout.

543
00:23:52,380 --> 00:24:00,320
I think one of the things is that there is they clearly need someone from publications to look at the documents they give to the people doing the Hugo ceremony,

544
00:24:00,320 --> 00:24:04,780
because there's no way you have the sixth of six people on the second sheet.

545
00:24:04,780 --> 00:24:05,340
Sure.

546
00:24:05,340 --> 00:24:13,240
You page break that shit so that it's all in some in one block because people are stressed out and you need to make it easy for them to see what it is they're doing.

547
00:24:13,240 --> 00:24:16,960
So like I can see that needed to be better on the paper.

548
00:24:16,960 --> 00:24:20,320
And I can imagine how awful you would feel if you did it.

549
00:24:20,320 --> 00:24:21,400
And I can see why she said that.

550
00:24:21,400 --> 00:24:23,180
But also it sounds excruciating.

551
00:24:23,180 --> 00:24:24,180
It was.

552
00:24:24,180 --> 00:24:34,160
And I think the fact that the last person was on a different sheet of paper really reveals that there was a lack of preparation, but also a system failure.

553
00:24:34,160 --> 00:24:40,660
I would guess that there is a system failure with whoever was in charge of compiling this, putting it together.

554
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:42,500
I don't think we can just pile on the hosts.

555
00:24:42,500 --> 00:24:47,000
I think that the, you know, the convention has plenty of responsibility for this.

556
00:24:47,000 --> 00:24:50,660
And I remain surprised that we have not heard from the convention about it.

557
00:24:50,660 --> 00:24:56,100
Especially because yesterday I saw a post on Blue Sky from Seattle Convention that said,

558
00:24:56,100 --> 00:24:58,080
Do you have feedback for us?

559
00:24:58,080 --> 00:25:00,700
Send your feedback to such and such email address.

560
00:25:00,700 --> 00:25:03,580
And I was like, I think.

561
00:25:03,580 --> 00:25:06,140
Ooh, I have feedback for you is what you thought.

562
00:25:06,140 --> 00:25:08,640
It is good to solicit feedback.

563
00:25:08,640 --> 00:25:20,800
But at this point, it makes it seem like it may not be taken too seriously because there has been a lot of feedback that has been offered voluntarily in the past week and no response to it.

564
00:25:20,800 --> 00:25:26,400
And I am all for taking a pause to consider one's words before issuing a statement.

565
00:25:26,400 --> 00:25:29,680
You know, I'm a lawyer, so I'm all about let's think before we talk.

566
00:25:29,680 --> 00:25:37,500
But I think like a just a preliminary, hey, we realize we screwed this up and hurt people and we are really sorry.

567
00:25:37,500 --> 00:25:38,240
More to come.

568
00:25:38,240 --> 00:25:41,220
Something like that would be a good idea.

569
00:25:41,220 --> 00:25:42,420
But we haven't seen that.

570
00:25:42,420 --> 00:25:49,880
And that's too bad because I do, you know, everybody that I dealt with with this convention seemed like a nice person with good intentions.

571
00:25:50,400 --> 00:25:52,740
And I think that they are nice people with good intentions.

572
00:25:52,740 --> 00:25:54,800
And so I am I'm confused.

573
00:25:54,800 --> 00:25:56,860
I've been confused by this whole thing.

574
00:25:56,860 --> 00:26:03,560
Yeah, I think like there's no doubt in my mind that the two hosts kind of they had good intentions.

575
00:26:03,560 --> 00:26:04,880
They have been around.

576
00:26:04,880 --> 00:26:08,520
They know that pronouncing names poorly is an issue.

577
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:16,880
And indeed, people have been finding the tweets from 2020 saying they were aware of like when, you know, George R.R. Martin did this.

578
00:26:17,640 --> 00:26:21,260
And I think we all remember kind of the well, I was watching it live.

579
00:26:21,260 --> 00:26:25,040
Remember the kind of uncomfortable or really situation.

580
00:26:25,240 --> 00:26:28,660
So I'm sure they were like doing their best to avoid that.

581
00:26:28,660 --> 00:26:33,380
But there's obviously been some failure and we don't know where.

582
00:26:33,380 --> 00:26:36,140
And I think you're right in saying, look, there could be multiple things.

583
00:26:36,140 --> 00:26:39,520
It could be that you do the run through with the script and it all works fine.

584
00:26:39,520 --> 00:26:41,580
But that's because you're in an empty theater.

585
00:26:41,580 --> 00:26:52,240
And then when there's thousands of people there, you get nervous and you get pages and you don't realize it until you get there, which is something that the ceremony organizers should be figuring out and addressing.

586
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:58,400
I'm absolutely sure that like once you've got one thing wrong, it snowballs.

587
00:26:58,400 --> 00:27:02,680
And you if you get the next thing wrong and notice it, then you start to feel even worse.

588
00:27:02,680 --> 00:27:07,640
And then you start to feel you have to kind of apologize on the spot and it just snowballs from there.

589
00:27:07,640 --> 00:27:11,800
But maybe we need to build in more guest presenters.

590
00:27:11,800 --> 00:27:13,280
So they had a couple of guest presenters.

591
00:27:13,280 --> 00:27:19,200
But maybe if you had a few more, that would at least give the main host kind of time to kind of, OK, I've got five minutes now.

592
00:27:19,200 --> 00:27:20,200
I'm going to chill.

593
00:27:20,200 --> 00:27:21,060
I'm going to regroup.

594
00:27:21,060 --> 00:27:22,960
I'm going to go back and start afresh.

595
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:25,460
You know, maybe they didn't have enough rehearsal time.

596
00:27:25,460 --> 00:27:29,380
Maybe they didn't get everything on time to do the rehearsals.

597
00:27:29,380 --> 00:27:31,020
Maybe they just didn't rehearse enough.

598
00:27:31,020 --> 00:27:33,940
Maybe they didn't spend enough time going over and over the names.

599
00:27:34,220 --> 00:27:35,800
But it all came from somewhere.

600
00:27:35,800 --> 00:27:40,360
And I think it's a bit lacking that they haven't said anything about it for over a week.

601
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:43,020
Even if it was just a quick look, it's the end of the con.

602
00:27:43,020 --> 00:27:43,860
We're traveling.

603
00:27:43,860 --> 00:27:45,460
We'll have a fuller statement later.

604
00:27:45,780 --> 00:27:49,660
So what I'm going to say here is that some things have been said on the Internet.

605
00:27:49,660 --> 00:27:57,040
So for context, I think we should probably say when George R. R. Martin made a similar mistake at the Hugo Awards in 2020,

606
00:27:57,040 --> 00:27:58,620
Kate Tempest Bradford tweeted,

607
00:27:58,620 --> 00:28:01,100
Did no one watch these videos before they loaded them up?

608
00:28:01,100 --> 00:28:02,520
Why are so many names mispronounced?

609
00:28:02,520 --> 00:28:04,060
And then followed that up with,

610
00:28:04,060 --> 00:28:11,040
Can I get 80 authors to sign an open letter telling the Hugo Awards to not allow people who allow presenters to mangled names to run the show anymore?

611
00:28:11,040 --> 00:28:15,040
Now, obviously, that's a bit different because the 2020 ceremony was videoed.

612
00:28:15,040 --> 00:28:17,240
And so really, it should have been possible to do retakes.

613
00:28:17,240 --> 00:28:24,600
But also, given that there has not been an apology and it has been over a week, that is interesting.

614
00:28:24,600 --> 00:28:29,820
I think it's also interesting if you have a strong opinion that these names are pronounced correctly.

615
00:28:29,820 --> 00:28:40,940
It is interesting that that would not go well when you do it, whether that is because you haven't rehearsed or whether it's because you've rehearsed loads and you just make a lot of mistakes on the night.

616
00:28:41,340 --> 00:28:48,500
Either way, if you think it's important and you know you've screwed up, you say sorry afterwards and you don't wait to say sorry.

617
00:28:48,500 --> 00:28:51,040
Kate Tempest Bradford skeeted to say,

618
00:28:51,040 --> 00:28:53,660
Hey everyone, hopping on here very quick to relay the following.

619
00:28:53,900 --> 00:28:59,640
I've not been on socials or the computer all week because I caught COVID right after the con and I've been attempted not to cough so hard my lung escapes.

620
00:28:59,640 --> 00:29:03,240
I wasn't aware about the convos about the Hugos until a couple of days ago.

621
00:29:03,240 --> 00:29:04,520
And she follows up with,

622
00:29:04,520 --> 00:29:07,100
Nissy and I plan to release a public statement apology shortly.

623
00:29:07,100 --> 00:29:09,660
We haven't yet because I'm still not really feeling great or coherent.

624
00:29:09,660 --> 00:29:13,440
And the matter deserves more thought and consideration than I am capable of right this second.

625
00:29:13,440 --> 00:29:15,420
I did want folks to know I'm not ignoring it.

626
00:29:15,460 --> 00:29:22,680
And so, yeah, I think they're clearly working on an apology, but it's not in the wake of the last five years of discourse.

627
00:29:22,680 --> 00:29:25,900
I feel one of the things we have learned is how to apologize.

628
00:29:25,900 --> 00:29:28,300
It's not hard.

629
00:29:28,300 --> 00:29:29,900
Well, it shouldn't be hard.

630
00:29:29,900 --> 00:29:30,800
It is hard.

631
00:29:30,800 --> 00:29:32,800
You have to be very brave to say sorry.

632
00:29:32,800 --> 00:29:35,640
But a good apology is I am really sorry.

633
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:38,940
I am sorry to the people whose names I mispronounced.

634
00:29:38,940 --> 00:29:40,400
It was unacceptable.

635
00:29:40,840 --> 00:29:42,740
And next time we will do differently.

636
00:29:42,740 --> 00:29:44,540
I just did that off the top of my head.

637
00:29:44,540 --> 00:29:46,080
It doesn't require an essay.

638
00:29:46,080 --> 00:29:46,820
No.

639
00:29:46,820 --> 00:29:53,540
And if you are writing an essay, that says to me that you're centering yourself in the apology and not centering the person that you need to apologize to.

640
00:29:53,540 --> 00:30:00,140
Because all of the things you want to put in there to explain why it happened, that's you justifying why it happened.

641
00:30:00,140 --> 00:30:01,320
That's not you apologizing.

642
00:30:01,320 --> 00:30:02,200
And it's very tempting.

643
00:30:02,200 --> 00:30:08,260
But when George R. R. Martin wrote like 3,000 word apology after Con Zeeland, it was like, no, George, you just need to say sorry.

644
00:30:08,260 --> 00:30:12,480
I don't need a massive diatribe about like how it all came to be.

645
00:30:12,480 --> 00:30:14,800
I just want to know you know you screwed up.

646
00:30:14,800 --> 00:30:16,760
Am I off base here, do you think?

647
00:30:16,760 --> 00:30:17,920
Or like, what do you reckon?

648
00:30:17,920 --> 00:30:20,580
Well, I do want to know why it happened.

649
00:30:20,580 --> 00:30:24,960
I mean, I would I think you are I agree with you that the sorry should just be sorry.

650
00:30:24,960 --> 00:30:26,780
And I think that that should come first.

651
00:30:26,780 --> 00:30:29,580
And then for me, I kind of do want an explanation.

652
00:30:29,580 --> 00:30:31,920
Like, why was someone's name on the second page?

653
00:30:31,920 --> 00:30:33,940
Why didn't they have pronunciation guides?

654
00:30:33,940 --> 00:30:38,560
I think that that helps us understand what we can do better next time.

655
00:30:38,560 --> 00:30:41,780
I want to know, did somebody not send this stuff?

656
00:30:41,780 --> 00:30:42,960
Did a file get lost?

657
00:30:42,960 --> 00:30:44,800
I mean, just what happened?

658
00:30:44,800 --> 00:30:52,100
Because I prefer to think that there were there was a series of accidents or something rather than people just didn't care.

659
00:30:52,280 --> 00:30:54,340
But I don't know, I guess the accidents are not caring.

660
00:30:54,340 --> 00:30:54,860
I don't know.

661
00:30:54,860 --> 00:30:55,760
I want to know what happened.

662
00:30:55,760 --> 00:30:56,720
Maybe it's just because I'm nosy.

663
00:30:56,720 --> 00:30:58,320
I think we want to know what happened.

664
00:30:58,320 --> 00:31:02,280
But also, I think 2026 onwards need to know what happened.

665
00:31:02,280 --> 00:31:04,500
And maybe that doesn't need to be super public.

666
00:31:04,500 --> 00:31:11,700
But I think like someone from 2026 needs to come out and say, yes, we have discussed this with the 2025 crew.

667
00:31:11,700 --> 00:31:13,000
And we have done a postmortem.

668
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:14,360
And we know what happened.

669
00:31:14,360 --> 00:31:17,400
And this is what we will do differently next time.

670
00:31:17,560 --> 00:31:20,100
And that definitely can be later.

671
00:31:20,100 --> 00:31:22,080
I think that's a reasonable middle ground.

672
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:28,160
So this may all be moot by the time this episode comes out because we may have the, you know, apology and more discussion.

673
00:31:28,160 --> 00:31:30,800
But that's how it stands for us at the moment.

674
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:32,640
We don't know what happened on the night.

675
00:31:32,640 --> 00:31:40,420
But I do hope that someone talked to some of the people whose names were missed off, which is Camilla Cole was missed off entirely.

676
00:31:40,420 --> 00:31:46,300
And they didn't list the names for, I think, Correo, Semiprozine or the Reddit Fantasy.

677
00:31:47,080 --> 00:31:51,580
And I don't know what, I mean, that's a discussion we've had before about how many names do you read out.

678
00:31:51,580 --> 00:31:57,920
But again, if they're expecting them to be read out and they weren't, then that would be nice for someone to discuss with them.

679
00:31:57,920 --> 00:31:58,860
Yep, I agree.

680
00:31:58,860 --> 00:32:01,680
I think the important part is for people to know what to expect.

681
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:11,460
Because if you don't know what to expect and you get there and the team before you or several teams before you are all read out and then yours isn't, I mean, it's impossible to not feel singled out by that.

682
00:32:11,460 --> 00:32:12,720
And you look singled out.

683
00:32:12,720 --> 00:32:17,520
So even if no one meant to single you out, the audience is also looking at it saying, oh, well, why didn't they read all of those?

684
00:32:17,520 --> 00:32:18,460
There must be some reason.

685
00:32:18,460 --> 00:32:21,820
And so I think setting, managing people's expectations.

686
00:32:21,820 --> 00:32:26,260
And then I am for creating a policy and just sticking with it.

687
00:32:26,260 --> 00:32:28,480
There are increasingly a lot of large teams.

688
00:32:28,640 --> 00:32:35,420
And so my thought as a member of a four-person team is it would make sense to use the team name and say, we use team names.

689
00:32:35,420 --> 00:32:40,660
Unless you are an individual, you know, you're an editor or you, you know, you're in best novel or something like that.

690
00:32:40,660 --> 00:32:41,340
You're an individual.

691
00:32:41,340 --> 00:32:43,300
I think use the team name.

692
00:32:43,300 --> 00:32:47,960
And I know that some people will not be happy with that, but everyone would be treated the same.

693
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:49,760
Expectations would be clear.

694
00:32:50,080 --> 00:33:00,300
So, yeah, I just kind of think let's pick something and do that so that we don't have people feeling surprised and hurt on what should be a really special occasion for them.

695
00:33:00,300 --> 00:33:00,900
Yeah.

696
00:33:00,900 --> 00:33:03,140
So it is, it's a thing.

697
00:33:03,140 --> 00:33:07,320
So there have been different approaches to this.

698
00:33:07,320 --> 00:33:11,620
Certainly it used to be that only three people could win rockets.

699
00:33:11,960 --> 00:33:19,160
So like Plockter, when Allison won for Plockter, they got three rockets and they wouldn't have been able to get more even if like they had wanted to.

700
00:33:19,160 --> 00:33:26,040
But I will also note, like looking at the number of people on each team, Carrera has 41 people.

701
00:33:26,040 --> 00:33:28,920
And that is, it's a lot of names to read out in a ceremony.

702
00:33:28,920 --> 00:33:38,760
Like I'm not saying all of those people, if they are all on the team, all of them get a rocket, all of them get the certificate and the pin, all of them go to the reception, all of them go to the ceremony.

703
00:33:38,760 --> 00:33:40,360
I'm not arguing any of that.

704
00:33:40,540 --> 00:33:45,540
But what I am saying is that like it is, it's going to take a couple of minutes to read all those names out.

705
00:33:45,540 --> 00:33:53,220
And especially if you're dealing with names that you're reading a pronunciation guide for and you're nervous, that might, you know, might not be smooth.

706
00:33:53,220 --> 00:33:58,060
And so I could see like a rule where you have like, you know, if you've got more than 20 people, we want to use a team name.

707
00:33:58,060 --> 00:34:00,160
I could see a rule that just says we use team names for everything.

708
00:34:00,160 --> 00:34:05,000
I would quite like it to just be like a decision that we make and stick to.

709
00:34:05,080 --> 00:34:10,500
The problem is like getting Worldcons to agree on a course of action voluntarily is impossible.

710
00:34:10,880 --> 00:34:17,140
And it seems like the sort of thing we don't want to mandate, like we don't want to go to the business meeting and try and do a constitutional amendment because that seems very heavy handed.

711
00:34:17,140 --> 00:34:18,960
So I don't know how you actually achieve it.

712
00:34:18,960 --> 00:34:26,920
And you do get the thing where like, you know, if you do have all your names on the slide and they're not read out, you do think, well, why did everyone else get and not us?

713
00:34:27,080 --> 00:34:31,780
And so I remember when it happened at Glasgow that...

714
00:34:31,780 --> 00:34:32,580
I think it was Chicago.

715
00:34:32,580 --> 00:34:34,140
You mean the semi-prosy one?

716
00:34:34,140 --> 00:34:35,100
It was Chicago.

717
00:34:35,100 --> 00:34:41,940
Charlie Jane Anders and Annalene Newitz were the Toastmasters and they read out Team Strange Horizons.

718
00:34:41,940 --> 00:34:48,380
